<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09142i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09142i">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09142i"> 142(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bitt (staple on ship)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>On some Popular Phrases / Nautical Origins</b> Expressions in everyday speech,&hellip; Every ship of the present day has twin pillars of iron called <mark>&ldquo;Bitts,&rdquo; fixed in convenient places round the deck for mooring the vessel</mark>. <small> <a name="II13mar24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#II13mar24"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (13 March 1924) 6/5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Bitt (naut.): One of the posts fastened in pairs in the deck or decks of a ship, for fastening cables, belaying ropes, etc. </mm> </dd></dl>
